userestrict.head: Ownership & Copyright
userestrict.p: Copyright has been transferred to Stanford University. All requests to reproduce, publish, quote from, or otherwise use collection materials must be submitted in writing to the University Archivist, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, California 94304-6064.
Restrictions also apply to digital representations of the original materials. Use of digital files is restricted to research and educational purposes.

prefercite.head: Cite As
prefercite.p: William Bradford Shockley Papers (SC0222). Department of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, Calif.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical Sketch
bioghist.p: Professor of engineering at Stanford (1958-1975; emeritus 1975- ). Shockley was co-recipient of the Nobel Prize in physics, 1956.

otherfindaid.head: Related Collections
otherfindaid.p: Stanford University Archives also holds William Spicer's William Shockley and eugenics collection, 1965-1970 (SC0864) and Isabel Steiner Karkau's William Shockley and eugenics collection, 1966-1973 (SC0595), as well as Shockley's father, William Hillman Shockley papers, circa 1860-circa 1920 (SC1108).. The Hoover Institution also holds the William Shockley miscellaneous papers, 1980 (80124).

scopecontent.head: Description of the Collection
scopecontent.p: Professional and personal papers relating to Professor Shockley's controversial interests in environment and genetic influences on intelligence; research on transistors and electronics; and science education. Also includes extensive family materials including diaries and correspondence.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The main accession is arranged in four series: 1. Telephone Conversations; 2. Correspondence; 3. Correspondence Enclosures; 4. May Bradford Shockley/Shockley Family Papers. Subsequent accessions to the collection follow.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II contains volumes of incoming and outgoing chronological correspondence files. A typed index, listing dates, names and institutional affiliation of all correspondence and correspondents is in the front of each volume. The files span the years 1958 - 1971. Subjects discussed in this correspondence include the importance of genetic factors in intelligence, the overpopulation problem and birth control, eugenics, student unrest (particularily,incidents at Stanford), environmental issues (specifically air pollution) and various requests for Dr. Shockley to speak, and for reprints of his articles. These files are stored in ten record storage boxes and two manuscript boxes.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series 3 consists of enclosures, received with incoming letters, which are filed separately from this incoming correspondence. These files are chronological and date from May 1958 to December, 1971. They fill twelve record storage boxes .

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series IV contains the personal papers of May Bradford Shockley, William B. Shockley's mother. Along with financial and legal records are correspondence with friends and family, dating back to May Shockley's youth in California and her life in a Nevada mining town around the turn of the century, and continuing until the early 1970's. Also included is correspondence and papers of other family members, including William Hillman Shockley (father of W.B.S.). Several journals of Sarah Hillman Shockley, 1859-1965, along with a draft of her autobiography and other writing efforts are in this series, as well as several diaries and address books belonging to May Bradford Shockley. In addition, there are two folders of genealogical information, one for W.H. Shockley, and the other for May B. Shockley's family. This series also contains many photographs, and several scrapbooks of the Shockley family, dating back to the 1860's.

May Bradford Shockley's papers also include some information on her son. One folder contains old school diplomas, commencement brochures and newsclippings about William B. Shockley. There is also intermittent correpondence from him and his wife, to M. B. Shockley, 1924-1966.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: WS was plaintiff in a libel suit against Cox Enterprises Inc., publisher of the Atlanta Constitution, and Roger Witherspoon, a journalist for the newspaper. The trial took place In Atlanta, Georgia in September 1984. Witherspoon, who is African American, profiled WS in an unfavorable light in a July 30th, 1980 article. The article, which was based on a series of interviews, suggested that WS’s eugenics program was essentially the same as that of Nazi Germany. After the Constitution refused to print a retraction, WS sought $1,250,000 in damages. WS won the suit, but was awarded one dollar. The case was appealed unsuccessfully. The file includes correspondence, essays, notes, articles, and several unfoldered bound volumes of legal transcripts.

scopecontent.p: This formal series for scientific papers was assigned numerical codes in a sequence with a "T" (and sometimes "R") prefix. scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains diaries, notebooks, artwork and correspondence, primarily from WS' parents William Hillman and May Bradford Shockley. The majority of Shockley family material in this accession was saved by WS following May's death in 1977. WS wrote about the experience in a commemorative booklet included here. May’s own files are mostly small sketches and paintings. Most photographs not attached to notebook pages have been moved to the Photographs series. See also May Shockley papers in first accession Series IV, other WHS diaries in Box 12 of the first accession, and the William Hillman Shockley papers, circa 1860-circa 1920 (SC1108)..

William and May Shockley approached the rearing of their only child in a very scientific manner, and subsequently there is a considerable amount of detail about the birth and childhood of WS (known here as “Billy”), including charts of his diet, health and growth and lists of books read to, as well as artwork, a lock of hair, and even a splinter removed from his face after a mishap on a front porch. References to his inquisitiveness, temper, stubbornness, and manual dexterity suggest much of what later characterized him.

The group of notebooks by WHS provide many insights about the Shockleys and life in Palo Alto in the teens. These notebooks feature diaries (some also doubling as correspondence to family members), notes, lists, clippings (most from the Daily Palo Alto News), and material related to his role in the Simplified Spelling movement. Some correspondence has been pasted in notebooks, including a telegram from William Randolph Hearst telegram in 1916.

The diaries make note of WHS’ involvement with the Engineers Club (of which he was Vice President), as well as his mining, real estate and other business ventures. Also revealed are interactions with friends (including the Hoovers), neighbors, and professors at Stanford, as well as accounts of excursions to Lake Lagunita, La Honda and elsewhere. WHS wrote about World War I even before the U.S. entered the conflict, and when Camp Fremont was built in Menlo Park, WHS took an interest in the recreation of soldiers. May was also active in food rationing, home economics and Belgian relief efforts during the war. Finally, the diaries chronicle the family’s travels in Los Angeles, New York, Florida, and Louisiana (where they bought a pet alligator), as well as London (where they were living when WS was born) and continental Europe.

Also grouped here are some unrelated WS personal files, such as material concerning his mountain climbing and magic trick interests, an art class notebook from Hollywood High School, an autograph book from Caltech, and a 1931 exercise pamphlet in which he posed as a model. This series also features later genealogy-related correspondence between WS and others.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Day planners, notebooks, and annotated desk calendars, unfoldered and arranged chronologically. Some were used only sporadically, particularly 1989. These notebooks contain both personal and professional information; 1955 notebooks have family correspondence, notes and correspondence about his divorce from Jean Shockley, as well as notes from his initial meeting with Beckman. 1961-1980 notebooks were numbered 10-35 and begin with his extended recovery from a serious automobile accident. Bohemian Club notebooks were transferred to other BC material in Box 62, and a 1932 autograph book from Caltech (including an autograph from Linus Pauling) was moved to the Shockley family/personal series.
